{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617565"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16476"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16476"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.15,0.3,0.1,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71204"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9167"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56678"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71204"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMultiple sclerosis is a chronic inflammatory demyelinating disease of the central nervous system that typically presents in young adults. Disease-modifying therapy is most effective when started early in the disease course.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes an appropriate disease-modifying therapy for reducing disability progression in multiple sclerosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous immunoglobulin","Plasma exchange therapy","Natalizumab","Regular methylprednisolone pulses","Oral prednisolone maintenance"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENatalizumab\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective disease-modifying therapy that prevents immune cell migration across the blood-brain barrier, reducing inflammation and slowing disability progression in multiple sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E has limited evidence in multiple sclerosis and is not recommended as routine therapy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma exchange therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe relapses unresponsive to first-line treatments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular methylprednisolone pulses\u003C/strong\u003E treat acute relapses but do not modify long-term disease progression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone maintenance\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended due to side effects and lack of evidence for long-term benefit\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDisease-modifying therapies like natalizumab are most effective when started early in the disease course to prevent accumulation of disability and reduce relapse frequency. Regular monitoring is required due to the risk of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Disease-modifying therapies in multiple sclerosis aim to reduce relapse frequency and slow disability progression.","Monoclonal antibodies like natalizumab prevent immune cell migration into the central nervous system.","Early intervention with disease-modifying therapy improves long-term outcomes in multiple sclerosis."],"references":["Hauser SL, Cree BAC. Treatment of Multiple Sclerosis: A Review. Am J Med. 2020 Dec;133(12):1380-1390.e2. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2020.05.049. Epub 2020 Jul 17. PMID: 32682869; PMCID: PMC7704606.","He A, Merkel B, Brown JWL, Zhovits Ryerson L, Kister I, Malpas CB, Sharmin S, Horakova D, Kubala Havrdova E, Spelman T, Izquierdo G, Eichau S, Trojano M, Lugaresi A, Hupperts R, Sola P, Ferraro D, Lycke J, Grand\u0027Maison F, Prat A, Girard M, Duquette P, Larochelle C, Svenningsson A, Petersen T, Grammond P, Granella F, Van Pesch V, Bergamaschi R, McGuigan C, Coles A, Hillert J, Piehl F, Butzkueven H, Kalincik T; MSBase study group. Timing of high-efficacy therapy for multiple sclerosis: a retrospective observational cohort study. Lancet Neurol. 2020 Apr;19(4):307-316. doi: 10.1016/S1474-4422(20)30067-3. Epub 2020 Mar 18. PMID: 32199096.","Talanki Manjunatha R, Habib S, Sangaraju SL, Yepez D, Grandes XA. Multiple Sclerosis: Therapeutic Strategies on the Horizon. Cureus. 2022 May 10;14(5):e24895. doi: 10.7759/cureus.24895. PMID: 35706718; PMCID: PMC9187186.","Selmaj K, Cree BAC, Barnett M, Thompson A, Hartung HP. Multiple sclerosis: time for early treatment with high-efficacy drugs. J Neurol. 2024 Jan;271(1):105-115. doi: 10.1007/s00415-023-11969-8. Epub 2023 Oct 18. PMID: 37851189; PMCID: PMC10769939."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56678"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56678"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:54:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:55:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9167"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71204"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\